NEWCASTLE DISEASE - EUROPE
**************************
A ProMED-mail post
Date: Mon, 23 Mar 1998 12:41:59 -0400
From: Dorothy Preslar <dpreslar@fas.org>
Source: Office International des Epizooties, Disease Information, Vol 11,
Nos 10 & 11, 6-20 Mar 1998

Outbreaks of Newcastle disease have been reported to the OIE by Denmark,
Czech Republic and Austria.
(1) DENMARK
Text of a fax received on 27 February 1998 from Dr E. Stougaard, Chief
Veterinary Officer, Ministry of Agriculture, Frederiksberg:
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: February 1998.
Estimated date of first infection: February 1998.
Location No. of outbreaks
Skelskoer, Vestsjaelland county 2
Description of affected population: two commercial turkey farms. Out of
140,000 susceptible birds, about 2200 were destroyed
Diagnosis: diagnosis made on 27 February 1998. Intracerebral pathogenicity
index: 1.75 and 1.84.
Source of agent / origin of infection: the origin of the disease is not yet
known, and is under investigation. Control measures during reporting
period: the flocks will be killed and rendered.

(2) CZECH REPUBLIC:
One week after a report of no further outbreaks recorded in the protection
and surveillance zones set up after the outbreak which occurred on 14
January 1998 in Hradec Kralove district and the announcement that
restrictions on the affected flock and the area concerned were lifted on 14
March 1998, here is the text of a fax received on 18 March 1998 from Dr L.
Celeda, Deputy Director of the State Veterinary Administration, Prague:
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, post-mortem and laboratory.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 16 March 1998.
Estimated date of first infection: 8 March 1998.
Location No. of outbreaks
Pardubice-Popkovice, Pardubice district
(bordering on Hradec Kralove district) 1
Description of affected population: backyard flock. Of 17 susceptible
birds, there were 4 deaths. 13 birds were destroyed.
Diagnosis:
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: State Veterinary Institute, Prague.
B. Diagnostic tests used: virus isolation.
Control measures during reporting period: stamping-out; 3-km protection
zone and 10-km surveillance zone set up; vaccination.
(3) AUSTRIA:

Text of a fax received on 19 March 1998 from Dr P. Weber, Chief Veterinary
Officer, Ministry of Health, Sports and Consumer Protection, Vienna:
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 13 March 1998.
Location No of outbreaks
Federal Province Vienna, 7th District 1
Description of affected population: hobby flock of pigeons. Out of 17
susceptible birds, there were 2 cases of the disease, 1 death and 1 bird
destroyed.
Diagnosis:
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: Federal Institute for the Control
of Animal Virus Diseases, Vienna.
B. Diagnostic tests used: virus isolation.
Source of agent / origin of infection: unknown (contact with free flying
pigeons?).
Control measures during reporting period: measures in accordance with
European Directive No. 92/66/EEC. Confinement of the remaining birds for
60 days after the disappearance of all clinical signs.
